# BirdCLEF+ 2026 Competition Project

## Communication Style
- Always answer in short, easy sentences.
- User is a remote sensing expert, beginner in deep learning and audio ML.
- Use remote sensing analogies when explaining audio concepts (bands = frequency bins, raster = spectrogram).

## Competition Summary
- Task: identify 234 wildlife species from audio in Pantanal, Brazil.
- Multi-label classification: each 5-second window can have multiple species.
- Metric: macro ROC-AUC (skips classes with no true positives).
- Submission: Kaggle Code Competition, CPU-only inference, 90 minutes max.

## Data Layout (Linux VM)
- Base: `/data/scratch/scienceteam/jupyter-mir/bird/Data/birdclef-2026/`
- `train_audio/` -- 35,549 clean clips, 206 species, OGG format
- `train_soundscapes/` -- 10,658 field recordings (66 labeled, 10,592 unlabeled)
- `train_soundscapes_labels.csv` -- 1,478 rows, multi-label, 75 species
- 28 species have NO individual training clips (25 insect sonotypes + 3 amphibians)
- `test_soundscapes/` -- hidden, populated only on Kaggle servers

## Environment
- Linux VM with A40 GPU (48GB VRAM) for training
- Conda env: `bird` (Python 3.11)
- Key packages: PyTorch, timm, librosa, torchaudio, tensorflow, birdnetlib

## Model Plan
- Phase A: EDA (DONE)
- Phase B: BirdNET baseline (DONE -- saw how it works on one clip)
- Phase C: Custom EfficientNet-B0 on mel spectrograms (NEXT)
  - Stage 1: train on train_audio
  - Stage 2: pseudo-label unlabeled soundscapes
  - Stage 3: fine-tune with soundscapes
  - Export to ONNX for CPU inference
